{"title_page": "2002 World Championship in Mahjong", "text_new": "The '''2002 World Championship in Mahjong''' was held at the Hotel Grand Place in [[Iidabashi, Tokyo|Tokyo, Japan]] from October 23 to 27 in 2002. The title for this competition was \"The Festival for Culture and Sport in Mah Jong\".\n\nThe competition ran under corporation of Ningbo City Mahjong Sport Association and Japan Mahjong Organizing Committee (JMOC). JMOC was formed with 4 Japanese organizations including Japan Mahjong Federation, All-Japan Mahjong Society, Japan Health Mahjong Association, Mahjong Museum.\n\n==Competition==\nThis championship is not certified as the official first worldwide championship in Mah jong because it had been held before [[World Mahjong Organization]] was formed in 2006.\n\nAlthough it was offered from China at first and it was going to be held in [[Ningbo]] which is known as the origin of [[Mah jong]], the location was moved to Japan because a large event was going to be held there.<ref>{{cite web |language=Japanese |first=Masahiro |last=Kanazawa |url=http://www1.tcue.ac.jp/home1/takamatsu/100124/100124-002.pdf |title=\u4e16\u754c\u9ebb\u96c0\u9078\u624b\u6a29\u5927\u4f1a\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 (About 2002 World Mahjong Championship)|accessdate=2012-04-29 |date=2010-06-26}}</ref>\n\nFor this reason, the competition was held at the Hotel Grand Palace in [[Iidabashi, Tokyo]]. 100 competitors with 25 teams from 8 nations: China, Japan, USA, Taiwan, Russia, Sweden, Netherlands took part in this competition. JMOC held primarily tournaments in Tokyo and Osaka.<ref>{{cite web |first=Rep |last=Martin |url=http://www.mahjongnews.com/en/index.php/wmc/wmc2007/49-tokyo2002.html |title=The First World Championship in Mahjong |accessdate=2012-04-29 |date=2007-11-01 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120227033306/http://www.mahjongnews.com/en/index.php/wmc/wmc2007/49-tokyo2002.html |archive-date=2012-02-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://baike.baidu.com/view/7780619.htm \u7b2c\u4e00\u5c4a\u4e16\u754c\u9ebb\u5c06\u9526\u6807\u8d5b 1st World Championship in Mahjong](in Chinese)</ref>\n\n==Results==\nThe names are ordered as Given name and Surname.\n\n===Individual===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=50%\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% |Rank\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=15%|Name\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=10%|Nationality\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=10%|Table Points\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=10%|Mini Points\n|-align=center\n|1\n|align=left |[[Mai Hatsune]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|Japan}}Japan\n|align=center |26\n|align=center |898\n|-align=center\n|2\n|align=left |[[John J. O'Connor (mahjong player)|John J. O'Connor]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|USA}}United States\n|align=center |26\n|align=center|759\n|-align=center\n|3\n|align=left |[[Y\u016bichi Ikeya]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|Japan}}Japan\n|align=center |24\n|align=center |892\n|-align=center\n|4\n|align=left |[[Aki Nikaid\u014d]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|Japan}}Japan\n|align=center |23\n|align=center |893\n|-align=center\n|5\n|align=left |[[Jin Li (mahjong player)|Jin Li]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|China}}China\n|align=center |23\n|align=center |443\n|-align=center\n|6\n|align=left |[[Tomohiro Yoshida]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|Japan}}Japan\n|align=center |22\n|align=center |691\n|-align=center\n|7\n|align=left |[[Quanze Wu]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|China}}China\n|align=center |22\n|align=center |622\n|-align=center\n|8\n|align=left |[[Caofang Huang]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|China}}China\n|align=center |22\n|align=center |583\n|-align=center\n|9\n|align=left |[[Masashi Sait\u014d]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|Japan}}Japan\n|align=center |21\n|align=center |232\n|-align=center\n|10\n|align=left |[[Junhao Cui]]\n|align=center |{{Flag icon|China}}China\n|align=center |20\n|align=center |970\n|-align=center\n|}\n\n===Team===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" width=100%\n!style=\"background: #e3e3e3;\" width=5% |